When we fetch for the data for first hibernate give us the data from the DB:
For the second time frst level cache gibes the data, so that no need to go DB.

1st 1s 1  :  Hibernadefaultly give 1st level cache . ex: 

package com.hybernates.java.hybernates_java;

import org.hibernate.Session;
import org.hibernate.SessionFactory;
import org.hibernate.Transaction;
import org.hibernate.cfg.Configuration;

public class CacheInHiber {



	public static void main(String[] args) {
		// TODO Auto-generated method stub
		
		
		Student s1=new Student();
		
		Configuration con=new Configuration();
		con.configure();
		con.addAnnotatedClass(Student.class);
		
		SessionFactory factory = con.buildSessionFactory();
		
		Session session1 = factory.openSession();
		//session1.persist(s1);
		session1.beginTransaction();
		session1.getTransaction().commit();
		
		
		System.out.println("First level cacheing");
		Object res = session1.get(Student.class, 1);
		
		System.out.println("obj1"+res);
		System.out.println("Second time");
		Object res1 = session1.get(Student.class, 1);
		
		System.out.println("obj2: "+res1);
		
		

	}

}

Second level cache:

1. add below dependecy to pom.xml

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.hibernate</groupId>
    <artifactId>hibernate-ehcache</artifactId>
    <version>5.6.15.Final</version>
</dependency>

//
<property name="hibernate.cache.provider_class">org.hibernate.cache.EhCacheProvider</property>
//



Enable Second Level Cache in hibernate.cfg.xml
<!-- Enable second level cache -->
<property name="hibernate.cache.use_second_level_cache">true</property>

<!-- Enable query cache (optional but useful) -->
<property name="hibernate.cache.use_query_cache">true</property>

<!-- Cache provider -->
<property name="hibernate.cache.region.factory_class">
    org.hibernate.cache.ehcache.EhCacheRegionFactory
</property>


2. Create a new file: Add ehcache.xml file
src/main/resources/ehcache.xml

<ehcache>
    <defaultCache
        maxEntriesLocalHeap="1000"
        eternal="false"
        timeToIdleSeconds="300"
        timeToLiveSeconds="600"
        overflowToDisk="false"/>

    <cache
        name="com.example.model.Employee"
        maxEntriesLocalHeap="500"
        timeToLiveSeconds="600"/>
</ehcache>


3.  Enable cache on Entity class

In your Entity class, add 
@Cacheable
@Cache(usage = CacheConcurrencyStrategy.READ_WRITE)



@generatedValue(strategy=GenerationType.AUTO)---> it increase the value automatically. and no need to give id manually if we add this annotation.



second way:
Hibernate mapping file not required(replacement of mapping file, we write below entity class).

@entity
@Table(name="Table name")

